name: 2-ethylhexylacetate
Reason: 2-ethylhexylacetate has a melting point that we can predict by considering its structural components. The basic unit for analysis is ethanol, which has a melting point of -114.15°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The introduction of two additional methyl groups (–CH3–) raises the melting point due to increased molecular weight and van der Waals forces. The ethyl group (–CH2–) introduces a slight decrease due to reduced molecular weight and van der Waals interactions. The acetate group (–COO–) adds approximately +10°C due to increased molecular weight and hydrogen bonding potential. The presence of a methyl group (–CH3–) can also contribute to the melting point due to increased molecular weight and van der Waals forces, estimated at around +10°C.
